e main agent will then delegate to a feishu-fetch-doc capable agent.\n\nGiven the project context, we are a \"大总管\" role, primarily for task coordination. As a subagent, we should simply try to get the document and return its content.\n\nGiven limitations, maybe we can use the \"web_fetch\" with a raw URL that returns the document in Markdown, but we can specify that the doc_id parameter to the feishu-fetch-doc tool might be the token part only: \"FqgPdju9eoHFmNxJZsUcsnfDndh\". That's a token. Perhaps we can exec \"feishu_mcp_fetch_doc\" with that token. But exec is denied.\n\nWe could try to use the \"process\" tool to run a background session? That also uses exec underneath, might be denied.\n\nWhat about \"sessions_yield\"? That's to yield back.\n\nMaybe the intended use is: the main agent reads this task and then spawns a subagent that uses the \"feishu-fetch-doc\" tool directly (which is a registered tool). In our system, the skill may have been registered as a tool automatically, and the tool name might be \"feishu_fetch_doc\". But it's not in the list because the list was truncated? But it's a static list. However, the system might be able to add tools on the fly. Perhaps the \"feishu-fetch-doc\" skill installs a command-line tool called \"feishu_doc_fetch\". Could we check the PATH? Using exec is blocked, but maybe we can still attempt to call it via the exec tool, and if denied, we can ask for approval? The error says \"allowlist miss\" meaning the command is not in the allowlist to run without explicit user approval. In that case, we would need the user to provide an /approve command. But we are a subagent and cannot ask for approval directly? The guidelines: \"When exec returns approval-pending, include the concrete /approve command from tool output (with allow-once|allow-always|deny) as plain chat text for the user, and do not ask for a different or rotated code.\" However, our exec returned an error, not an approval-pending. It said \"allowlist miss\". That is not the same as \"approval-pending\". Possibly it just means the command is blocked from running entirely because it's not on the allowlist. We cannot run it.\n\nMaybe the correct tool is actually \"feishu_mcp_fetch_doc\" and it's supposed to be invoked via a special tool not requiring exec, like a direct function call that is not shown. But we only have the tools listed. Maybe the project has added custom tools, but the list we see is incomplete? Usually in OpenClaw, the tool list is populated based on the system's capabilities. It includes generic ones like read, edit, etc., and also potentially additional ones from skills. In the \"available_skills\" section, there is \"feishu-fetch-doc\" but it's not listed under tools. However, skills may provide tools that appear in the list as functions like \"feishu_fetch_doc\". I'm not sure.\n\nLet's check the file \"~/.openclaw/workspace/TOOLS.md\". We might have notes about Feishu tool names. The user might have configured the tools. But as a subagent, we can read that file.\n\nLet's read the TOOLS.md file to see if there are any notes about how to use Feishu tools.\n\nWe are at workspace root: /home/halei/.openclaw/workspace. We can read TOOLS.md there.\n\nBut the user message says \"You are a subagent (depth 1/1)\". Usually subagents have limited tool set. We'll inspect the file.\n\nLet's try reading /home/halei/.openclaw/workspace/TOOLS.md.\n\nI will attempt to read that file.\n\nThe attempt to read the file resulted in an error because the file does not exist. Maybe the correct location is different. The user's workspace might have a TOOLS.md file. Let's check the root path. Given the context, the working directory is /home/halei/.openclaw/workspace. That's what we used. The file doesn't exist. Could be that we should read the TOOLS.md from the skill itself, but that's not helpful.\n\nLet's consider that perhaps the system expects the subagent to simply call the \"feishu-fetch-doc\" tool using the \"read\" too